---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import TerminalBlock from "../components/TerminalBlock.astro";
import ChapterHeading from "../components/ChapterHeading.astro";
import ModesTable from "../components/ModesTable.astro";
import VaultCompare from "../components/VaultCompare.astro";

const installCmd =
  "curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/patrickmvla/bocek/main/install.sh | bash";
---

<Base title="bocek — engineering with evidence, not vibes">
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="hero-wash pointer-events-none absolute inset-0"></div>
    <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 pt-20 pb-28 sm:pt-28 sm:pb-36">
      <div class="mb-8 flex items-center gap-3">
        <span
          class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >bocek · v0</span
        >
        <span class="h-px w-12 bg-border"></span>
        <span
          class="font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-muted-foreground"
          >for claude code</span
        >
      </div>

      <h1
        class="font-heading text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-foreground sm:text-6xl sm:leading-[1.05]"
      >
        The model is a dataset.
        <br />
        <span class="text-muted-foreground">Treat it like one.</span>
      </h1>

      <p
        class="mt-8 max-w-2xl font-sans text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
      >
        Ask for output, you get the median of everything ever written. Ask for
        evidence — then challenge it — and you get the best of a thousand
        senior engineers, filtered through your judgment.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10">
        <TerminalBlock command={installCmd} title="~ — install bocek" />
      </div>

      <p
        class="mt-4 font-mono text-[11px] tracking-tight text-muted-foreground"
      >
        requires <span class="text-foreground">git</span> ·
        <span class="text-foreground">curl</span> ·
        <span class="text-foreground">jq</span> — then
        <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >bocek on</code
        > in any project
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 01 — the problem -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="problem"
    number="01"
    title="The default output is mediocre by definition."
    kicker="the problem"
  >
    <div class="space-y-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      <p>
        An LLM is a prediction engine. It produces the most statistically likely
        output given its training data. The majority of that training data is
        mediocre code — Stack Overflow answers, tutorial projects, boilerplate
        repos, average production codebases.
      </p>
      <p>
        When you say <span class="text-foreground">"build me a checkout API,"</span>
        the model doesn't think about your specific constraints. It produces the
        average checkout API from its training data. That average includes every
        shortcut, every missing edge case, every <span class="text-foreground"
          >"good enough"</span
        > decision from every codebase it's seen.
      </p>

      <blockquote
        class="my-8 border-l-2 pl-6 font-heading text-lg leading-snug text-foreground"
        style="border-left-color: var(--accent-amber);"
      >
        Every ungrounded decision makes the next decision worse — because the
        model has less ground truth to reason from.
      </blockquote>

      <p>
        By decision twenty, the inventory locking strategy was never chosen (it
        defaulted to none), the error contract was never specified, the auth
        token lifecycle was never designed. Every new feature interacts with
        twenty unexamined assumptions. The model can't help, because the model
        doesn't know which behaviors are intentional and which are accidents.
      </p>
    </div>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 02 — the shift -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="shift"
    number="02"
    title="Ask for evidence, not output."
    kicker="the shift"
    variant="alt"
  >
    <div class="space-y-8 text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      <p>
        The model has read every architecture post-mortem, every scaling
        failure, every production incident write-up. It knows how Stripe handles
        idempotency. It knows why optimistic locking fails under flash-sale
        conditions. But when you ask for output, it gives you the average — not
        because it doesn't know better, but because you didn't ask for better.
      </p>

      <blockquote
        class="my-8 border-l-2 pl-6 font-heading text-lg leading-snug text-foreground"
        style="border-left-color: var(--accent-amber);"
      >
        Design tokens are investment tokens. Implementation tokens without
        design are waste tokens.
      </blockquote>

      <div class="my-4 grid gap-px overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-border/60 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="bg-background p-6">
          <div class="mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
            <span class="h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full bg-muted-foreground/60"></span>
            <span
              class="font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-muted-foreground"
              >ungrounded ask</span
            >
          </div>
          <p class="font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
            "Build me a checkout API."
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
            → median code from the training data
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-background p-6">
          <div class="mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
            <span
              class="h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full bg-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
            ></span>
            <span
              class="font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
              >grounded ask</span
            >
          </div>
          <p class="font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-foreground">
            "Show me how Stripe handles idempotency in their node SDK, then
            challenge my approach to inventory locking."
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
            → the best of the training data, filtered through your judgment
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Stop treating the model as an executor. Start treating it as an evidence
        source and an adversarial reviewer. You are the judge — you provide
        taste, context, and the final call. The model presents evidence and
        challenges it. When you override it, the vault records your reason.
      </p>
    </div>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 03 — the modes -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="modes"
    number="03"
    title="Six modes. Each demands something from you."
    kicker="the modes"
  >
    <p
      class="mb-10 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
    >
      Modes aren't features — they're contracts. The model doesn't accommodate
      weak reasoning. It escalates.
    </p>
    <ModesTable />
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 04 — enforcement -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="enforcement"
    number="04"
    title="Three layers of defense. The first one costs zero tokens."
    kicker="enforcement"
    variant="alt"
  >
    <p class="mb-10 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      Instructions degrade as context grows — context rot is structural, not a
      bug. So Bocek doesn't trust the model's memory to enforce its own
      contracts. Each layer catches what the previous misses.
    </p>

    <div class="divide-y divide-border/60 border-y border-border/60">
      <div class="grid gap-4 py-7 sm:grid-cols-[9rem_1fr] sm:gap-10">
        <div>
          <div
            class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >
            layer 01
          </div>
          <div class="mt-1 font-heading text-base font-semibold text-foreground">
            the hook
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
          <p>
            A bash script that runs outside the context window. It reads
            <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >.bocek/mode</code
            > and blocks <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >Edit</code
            >, <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >Write</code
            >, and the Bash workarounds the model actually reaches for —
            <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >sed&nbsp;-i</code
            >, <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >python&nbsp;-c</code
            >, shell redirects.
          </p>
          <p class="font-heading text-[11px] tracking-tight text-foreground">
            zero tokens · non-bypassable · can't degrade
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid gap-4 py-7 sm:grid-cols-[9rem_1fr] sm:gap-10">
        <div>
          <div
            class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >
            layer 02
          </div>
          <div class="mt-1 font-heading text-base font-semibold text-foreground">
            the primitive
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
          <p>
            An 800–2,000 token contract the model loads into context. It
            specifies what the mode demands, how to calibrate response to the
            human's reasoning, and when to stop and flag. Works while attention
            holds — which is most of the time.
          </p>
          <p class="font-heading text-[11px] tracking-tight text-foreground">
            in-context · degrades with length · catches what the hook can't
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid gap-4 py-7 sm:grid-cols-[9rem_1fr] sm:gap-10">
        <div>
          <div
            class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >
            layer 03
          </div>
          <div class="mt-1 font-heading text-base font-semibold text-foreground">
            session restart
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
          <p>
            Your reset button. When context rots, start a fresh session.
            <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >state.md</code
            > and the compiled vault mean the new session inherits every resolved
            decision. Not a blank slate — a continuation.
          </p>
          <p class="font-heading text-[11px] tracking-tight text-foreground">
            manual · full recovery · the vault is the memory
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="mt-10 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      Nothing registers at startup. No persona, no skills loaded, no always-on
      instructions — every token in context is a token you chose to load.
    </p>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 05 — the vault -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="vault"
    number="05"
    title="The vault is the product. The code is downstream."
    kicker="the vault"
  >
    <p class="mb-10 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      Decisions, rejected alternatives, contracts, research — captured in
      markdown, compiled for the model on demand. New sessions aren't blank
      slates. They continue.
    </p>

    <VaultCompare />

    <p class="mt-10 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      Two formats, one direction. Obsidian-style markdown is the source of
      truth; per-feature files are compiled lazily — only when implementation
      mode needs them, only if the source has changed. No sync step. No stale
      artifacts. The vault travels with the code.
    </p>
  </ChapterHeading>

</Base>
